howItWorks: |
  <h2>How this raised bed soil calculator works</h2>
  <p>The calculator multiplies bed length &times; width &times; fill depth, then multiplies by the number of beds. It converts the result into cubic feet, cubic yards, and bags.</p>
  <h2>Soil settling note</h2>
  <p>Freshly filled beds often settle after watering and planting. A small overage helps reduce the chance that you need another store trip.</p>
relatedProse: |
  <p>For broader lawn or garden areas, use the <a href="/calculators/topsoil.html">Topsoil Calculator</a> to estimate cubic yards or bags.</p>
  <p>After filling your bed, the <a href="/calculators/mulch.html">Mulch Calculator</a> can help estimate mulch for moisture retention and weed control.</p>
  <p>Adding paths around your beds? Try the <a href="/calculators/paver.html">Paver Calculator</a> for pavers, base gravel, and sand.</p>
faq:
  - q: "How do I calculate soil for a raised bed?"
    a: "Multiply bed length by width by fill depth. This calculator converts the depth from inches to feet and estimates cubic feet, cubic yards, bags, and cost."
  - q: "How deep should soil be in a raised garden bed?"
    a: "Many vegetables grow well with 10 to 12 inches of soil or more. Root crops and larger plants may benefit from deeper beds."
  - q: "How much soil do I need for a 4x8 raised bed?"
    a: "A 4x8 bed filled 12 inches deep needs 32 cubic feet of soil before overage. If the depth is different, the soil volume changes proportionally."
  - q: "Should I fill a raised bed completely with bagged soil?"
    a: "You can, but large beds may require many bags. Bulk garden soil or a raised bed mix may be more practical for bigger beds."
  - q: "Should I add overage for raised bed soil?"
    a: "Yes. Soil settles after watering and planting, so a 5–10% buffer is often helpful when filling a new bed."
  - q: "What is the difference between topsoil and raised bed soil?"
    a: "Topsoil is a general soil material, while raised bed mixes are often blended for drainage, nutrients, and structure. Product quality varies by supplier."
  - q: "Can I use garden soil in a raised bed?"
    a: "Many raised bed products are designed for this use. Avoid using dense, poor-draining soil that may compact heavily in a contained bed."
  - q: "Why did my raised bed soil level drop?"
    a: "New soil settles as air pockets collapse, organic matter decomposes, and watering compacts the mix. It is normal to top off beds over time."
  - q: "How many bags of soil do I need?"
    a: "Bag count depends on bed volume and bag size. Enter the cubic-foot size listed on the bag label for the most accurate estimate."
  - q: "Should I mix compost into raised bed soil?"
    a: "Compost can improve organic matter and nutrients, but the right amount depends on your soil mix and what you are growing."
